Equivalent annual cost is a way to compare two projects that have different lifespans. It uses the annual costs as basis as to which project is more beneficial to the firm. It can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Equivalent annual cost}&=\dfrac{\text{Net present value}}{\text{Annuity factor}}
\end{aligned}$$

To get the net present value, we will use this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Net present value}&=-\text{Initial cost}-(\text{Operating cash flow} \times \text{Annuity factor}
\end{aligned}$$

To get the annuity factor, we will use an annuity table using the required return and the lifespan of the project. For **Machine A**, the corresponding annuity is $4.35526$. For **Machine B**, the corresponding rate is $5.75902$
